Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized travel agencies in the ČSSR at the time: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autotourist.
The travel agencies at that time only sold travels to the socialist Eastern bloc countries, and in the West, only the chosen ones were allowed.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the DDR), to the Soviet Union (Sotchi on the Peninsula of Crimea on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania on the Black Sea and to Hungary on the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972 when one was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-west course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that even citizens of the Eastern bloc (also the Czechoslovakias) were not allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even then travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but then you had to buy huge snakes or stay in the sleeping bag before the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even this has not been the case for a long time.
The so-called currency commitment - the condition for a trip to the West - was granted only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovakia currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without a foreign currency commitment it would have been impossible to retrieve the necessary financial resources (western currency) for a trip to the West.
Most Czechs therefore spent their holidays in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dates - a habit that lasts until today.
The whole revolution of 1989 followed a travel revolution of the Czechs on foot.
While until 1989 a holiday in the DDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox, which you are no longer aware of today, is the fact that you were unable to travel to the Czechs' most popular country of holiday until 1989, because it was part of the Yugoslavia of that time.
From the beginning of the nineties of the last century, the foreign exchange obligation to the neighbouring Western European countries has been lifted, giving rise to a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could simply not get enough from their trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
For example, the Czech holidaymakers slept in the park tent on travel to Paris, because who would have had the money for accommodation at the hotel or in a pension at that time.
A typical feature of travel abroad by Czechs was a full-packed bag with preserves, beer and permanent sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades, our tourists could finally buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and thus the average wages increased, which in 1997 came into another important moment.
Thanks to increased demands for travel, the travel agencies started regularly to prepare travels by charter flights after 1997, making the flight trips, thanks to the possibility to negotiate quantity discounts, incredibly discounted compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, already had currencyless payments with all the highly developed countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-central" travel was in 2000, when thanks to the high demand the first direct charter flight was completed to an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying annually in far-reaching sunny countries; this year you are flying 12 exotic destinations directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 Czechs travel annually in exotic countries!
Another important moment in the era, which marked our "post-revolutionary" development, came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely ranked among the highly developed countries of the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than 15 tsd. CZK per capita for a single holiday stay including the cost at the holiday resort.
