Climate intrusions inhibited the economy
In the first year when Mario López Valdez was in the government, unemployment and black labour increased in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
In 2011 Sinaloa's economic history will be remembered. It is the first year in which Mario López Valdez, who called himself the initiator of change and gave great hopes about economic growth, is the government. However, as a result of climate disruptions, growth cannot be mentioned, but, on the contrary, the main economic indicators have worsened.
The low temperatures in February caused not only millions of losses in agriculture, but also limited the growth of the state economy and resulted in a general decline of 3.6% in economic activity in the first quarter.This is mainly due to the historical decline in agricultural development by 31.16%, which has slowed down further economic sectors.
According to a report published by the Consejo Mexicoo para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development), 582 000 hectares of agricultural lands were damaged, of which 78.03 per cent were completely and the remaining 21.07 per cent were partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity until November has led to a continuous increase in unemployment in the Mexican state. The Institute Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter of the year, since from January to March 55,053 people in Sinaloa had no employment, which corresponds to 4.53 per cent of the working population. In the second quarter the unemployment rate increased to 5.28 per cent and from July to September to 6.19 per cent, resulting in 74 000 unemployed people in Sinaloa, which is 18,969 more than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa in the year is based on several factors. Economics scientist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), commented, the policy of public institutions indirectly explains the growing unemployment.
"What we are currently seeing is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors, including liquidity losses on the market due to the reductions in the legislation adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who are illegally accumulating dollars it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them or use them for anything else," he said.
Stop migration
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment also has a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country looking for work abroad, especially in the United States, has declined, on the one hand because of the problems of entry and, on the other hand, because it is also difficult to find work there. These people are staying here and looking for work, which makes unemployment rise," he says.
Black work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious, taking into account the high proportion of black labour, which, according to INEGI, includes 60.38 per cent of the employees working in the country without paying into the social security cash.
Unemployment and black labour are the lowest wages throughout Mexico, according to the statistics of the Institute of Mexican Social Security (Mexico Social Insurance Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Regal Employment and Social Welfare Authority in Mexico).
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5352 pesos by September, which is much lower than the government average of 7375 pesos.
Reduction of ADI
In addition to reducing economic activity and increasing unemployment, in 2011, the strongest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) has been recorded over the past decade. According to Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI amounted to US$ 630 597 from January to June, corresponding to 87.74 per cent of the deficit compared to US$ 5 143 312 in the same period of the previous year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Regal Authority for Economic Development) recorded a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies from the tertiary sector.
The debts
In the light of the economic crisis, the national government requested a loan of 3 000 000 000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities in July at the National Congress. The National Congress approved a loan of 200 600 000 pesos, but no positive impact of debt on any of the economic sectors in the country could be found by November.
Reactions
For the representatives of entrepreneurship, Mario López Valdé's first year of government revealed his inability.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (State Chamber of Manufacturing in Mexico) said that no efforts were made in 2011 to harmonise the views of different sectors, including the national government.
"The economic activity in Sinaloa was really very difficult this year. It has to be worked hard to recover the land lost this year and in 2012 we have to double our efforts. The efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the well-united government team, have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Long-term economic development
Loredo López stated that events such as the Frost at the beginning of the year complicated and slowed the economic development of the country.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the freezing. One of the most important effects is a slow economy that is not in motion enough to create an economic dynamic that could produce an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. Therefore, we will finish the year far below our expectations," he said.
Redefined appeal
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, Chairman of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Mexican Business Association) in Sinaloa said that the state must be driven to more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe it is necessary to develop a long-term programme for re-determining the economic vocation and line of the country, because it is important to activate all material and human resources of Sinaloa," he said.
There's a lot to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that guides the government's efforts on better tracks.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress with the government.
"There are areas in which one can say that the government has acted more extensively. What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
