The Court approves for 2015 the transition to digital television in Mexico
The transition of analogue to digital signals has been one of the most important changes worldwide in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) rejected the constitutional lawsuits filed by the Senate and the House of Deputies against the Bureau's office and, in the light of the lack of eight votes necessary to challenge the law, which must be forwarded from analogue to digital signals from 2021 to 2015.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, was of the opinion that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his responsibilities when he issued the decree of law with details on switching to digital terrestrial television.
This decision rejected the constitutional dispute initiated by the Senate because it did not receive the required qualified majority of eight votes in order to allow the court to decide on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality.
In the project for the complaint prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, it was proposed to declare the decree of law unconstitutional, since the regulation of radio and television is the responsibility of the Comisión Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico) and therefore the decree of law would be contrary to the hierarchical principles and reservations of law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero themselves voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed constitutional complaints against the Decree. After the adoption of the lawsuits, Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer applied the Decree and discontinued all activities for the establishment of digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the complaint submitted by the Chamber of Deputies without entering the debate on the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero was also responsible.
In his contribution, the Prime Minister stated that he was not in agreement with the project's arguments, in the sense that the state government should not regulate the measures to be taken by public administration with general rules.
"I don't think that if this were to be done, the independence of the regulatory body would be impaired." She also recalled that the central government is responsible for planning strategic policies, such as the telecommunications sector, for constitutional reasons, because it is responsible for state affairs.
Replacement of analogue signals by digital is one of the most important changes that have taken place throughout the world in recent years and results in better use of the radioelectric spectrum, increased signal quality and more channels.
The delaying of the transition, she said, is a delay in the enjoyment of digitalisation, which is a decision in the public interest, which has not only technical aspects, "because it covers economic, social, political and security aspects."
These issues, she stressed, "required the action of the whole system, according to the principle of economic governance by the state, they included a group of features that put the Constitution into the hands of the central government."
She recalled that many countries had already implemented the digital changeover worldwide, via the government, although they had highly specialized facilities.
It could not be concluded that the government would intervene in the powers of the Congress by issuing the contested decree, because the laws adopted by the legislation would be respected," she assured.
The possibility of counting the number of votes in Michoacán individually is considered
According to PREP, the difference between the first and second place in the Governor's election is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
This year, the possibility of the single counting of the voting table is a reality in the elections in Michoacán, because according to the data issued by the Programa de Resultados Elections Preliminares (PREP), the difference between the first and second place in the Governor's elections is close to 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 have not yet been counted.
In this sense, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, reminded that, just on 9 November last, the electoral body had adopted a number of rules to harmonise local rules with the federal reforms in electoral matters.
It should be remembered that Michoacán had not adapted his political constitution, his electoral law or his law on electoral justice to the reforms adopted by the Congress, so that they had not entered into force during this election round. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided its publication in the State indicator within the time limits set for it, with the argument to have no objections.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) decided on the Constitutional Complaint filed by the local legislative authorities and judged the voice of the State Commissioner on the constitutional reforms as "invalid and unlawful", as he did not have the right to "decide or to apply a veto against it".
María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained in an interview on the possibility of the individual counting of votes that the Consejo General del IEM now had the possibility that the local electoral authority could count the voting list partially or completely.
For example, under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be partially counted The results in the minutes do not agree; the minutes on the counting and calculation of votes are in fact not available, it is not in possession of the chairman of the electoral committee or there are obvious errors or amendments in the minutes.
In addition, the total counting of the full-filled ballots can be done if there is a difference between the suspected winner and the second-place winner, which is equal to or less than one percent, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an express request from the party-or coalition president, who is the second of those candidates.
The counting of votes may also take place in its entirety if, after the completion of the regular calculation, it is found that the difference between the alleged winner and the candidate in second place is equal or less than one percent, provided that an explicit request is made by a representative of the party whose candidate has become second. In this case, the electoral packages which have been suspended from a partial counting would be excluded.
It is worth mentioning that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation, where, according to PREP, the difference between the first and the second place is almost 0.16%, although the votes of 129 out of 923 electoral protocols have not yet been counted.
