Wednesday the formation of the new Italian government
The designated Prime Minister, Mario Monti, meets tomorrow with the President of Italy to present to him the new government, which is to offer the head of the crisis that Italy has led to the outbreak of economic collapse.
The designated Prime Minister, Mario Monti, meets tomorrow with the President of Italy to present to him the new government, which is to offer the head of the crisis that Italy has led to the outbreak of economic collapse.
A statement from the Presidential Palace announced that the Monti appointed on Sunday would meet on Wednesday with the President of the State, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm the formation of government.
It is expected that he will present a majority of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new Prime Minister will take office.
Monti said he would present to the President of the State the results of the discussions with the political parties on the formation of government.
"I want to reaffirm my absolute confidence in the ability of our country to cope with these difficult times," said the former EU Commissioner to the journalists.
Monti did not expressly confirm the formation of government, but his comments show that the obstacles have been overcome.
The "frame is now well set," he added.
Monti has managed to form a government in less than three days, which is much less time than normal. At the same time, Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has driven the cost of debt to an intolerant level.
The new government led by the former EU Commissioner Monti must adopt a tough savings package that was called for by the euro politicians to regain confidence in Italy.
The pressure on Monti's hurry was still intensified by the volatile market situation, resulting in a 7% interest burden on Italian government bonds for 10 years, which corresponds to the level in which Greece and Ireland were forced to apply for the European rescue umbrella.
Emma Marcegaglia, President of the Italian Confindustria Industry Association, told the press after a meeting with Monti, "We said we would support this government in every way."
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency.
The success prospects of Montis were greatly increased by the support of the PDL party by Silvio Berlusconi, who had to resign on Saturday as a result of the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are intended to achieve good results," said Angelino Alfano, Secretary of the middle law party.
The support of the PDL, the largest party in Italy, is essential, because so far many of its members have voted against a majority of technocrats, which Monti is currently forming.
Support from Parliament
The new Monti government needs strong parliamentary support to implement the likely unpopular savings measures.
Resistance to his efforts or the delay in the reform could again lead to a devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks also exercises pressure with its indication that Montis' failure is a disaster.
Monti began on Monday with his discussions with political parties, trade unions and entrepreneurial associations as well as with youth and women's organisations.
The round of meetings is scheduled to be concluded on Tuesday evening.
Monti was appointed this Sunday by Napolitano, who has launched an extremely rapid change of government in response to the crisis.
Recent breathing up at the end of last week, when it was known that Berlusconi would resign, due to the uncertainty about the success of the new Prime Minister, the costs of Italian bonds have again reached critical limits.
A rescue of Italy with a government debt of EUR 1.8 billion would be too much for the current EU rescue screen.
Monti said that his government should last until the next elections that are expected to take place in 2013, despite the predictions that politicians will give him only time to implement the reforms, instead of prefering the elections.
Monti stated that he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that this should be made up of only technicians, an indication of their concerns regarding the procedure imposed by the pressure of the financial markets.
Political sources point out that mutual mistrust and disagreements between the parties make the involvement of people from political life complicated.
