Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official deployment led by the President of Uruguay José Mujica and consisting of several ministers and entrepreneurs will start their visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss political issues in the region.
Mujica meets with his Mexican official colleague Felipe Calderón next Wednesday. According to the President of Uruguay, this will be the highlight of his booked schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of the Uruguayans living in Mexico.
The meeting of both presidents in the city of Guadalajara "suitable for the exchange of information on all policy areas between the two countries", announced the Presidential Office of the South American country on its website.
According to local media, Mujica sought Calderón's support for the incident with France when the French government leader Nicolas Sarkozy at the G20 summit in the city of Cannes put the South American country on a list of tax paradises.
In his discourse, Sarkozy threatened to exclude those countries that still appear as tax paradises from the international community, which was rejected by Uruguay and brought a question to his ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group consisting of the most powerful emerging and developed countries in the world. Since January this year there has been an agreement on the exchange of tax information to avoid duplication with the South American country.
In recent years, the Government of Uruguay has tried to speed up the implementation of agreements for the exchange of tax information in order to be removed from the "green list" of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), which is the subject of countries that have not introduced all international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
A free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay has been established at a commercial level since 2004, which has contributed to an increasing trade of goods between the two countries.
