MSS announces a research protocol for finding the gene for obesity
She runs a research project on finding the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, supported by IPN specialists.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Mexican Social Insurance Institute) announced that it is conducting a research project on the discovery of the gene of obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and youth" to identify genetic markers associated with overweight.
Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Medical Research Department, Focus Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI stated that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritional specialists and social workers was established.
This team is supported by specialists and students from the postgraduate course at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and at the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested persons can come to the IMSS sports sites in the valley of Mexico, where tests with children and young people are carried out every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the investigation started on the Cuauhtémoc sports site (west of the state of Mexico) and continued since 8 October on the Nezahualcóyolt sports site (east of the state of Mexico).
When the target is reached from 500 to 600 investigators, the study will be continued on the sports site of Independencia (in the south of the capital district) and completed on the site of Morelos (in the north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study was to learn from factors and the role of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors for Mexican children and adolescents in the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the World Diabetes Day he stated that it was intended that three thousand children and young people aged six to 14 should complete nutrition-related questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and family history to control risk factors that may lead to diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He further concluded that on the above Saturdays the subjects were measured (weight, size, waist size), their blood pressure controlled and blood levels such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (an attempt to identify genes associated with obesity at child age).
Cruz López stressed that this investigation would be carried out in response to the concern of health care workers about the alarming increase in young people's weight.
"The health surveys from 1999 and 2006 showed that in almost six years the proportion of fatty boys increased by 77 percent and the proportion of girls with obesity by 47 percent. Also, overweight increased dramatically," stressed the IMSS specialist.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the people of Mexico differed from that of other peoples.
He claimed that an (e) Mexican (in) average was 65 per cent of Indian-American, 30 per cent of European and 5 per cent of African origin, which was reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
Generally speaking, he explained that the genetics of obesity were expressed in the inability to burn out the surplus of energy (calorie), so that it was stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the subjects would be a comprehensive study of the children to determine whether they had a degree of overweight or obesity.
It would even investigate the presence of dark skin folding in the neck and in the inner arm (acanthosis) indicating the likelihood of metabolism disorders and pre-stage diabetes.
All information would be treated confidentially and communicated to the parents in writing by the doctors. The doctors will explain to the parents all the measurement results and suggest changes in the lifestyle that are appropriate to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there were three basic factors responsible for overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of exercise, i.e. lack of exercise in everyday life, spend most of the day before TV and use transport equipment, instead of walking short paths.
The high calorie intake, i.e. increased consumption of sugared beverages and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, Hamburgers, etc.), along with a high fat and protein intake, as well as genetics to be analysed in this research project.
Asphalt prevents blowholes from UNAM
Rafael Herrera, researchers at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University UNAM developed modified asphalts with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs that go out of the road surface were respected, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200 000 holes if the rainy time at the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (the city area of the valley of Mexico) broke out, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM University, warned and assured that if the occurrence and maintenance of the asphalt layer were appropriate, the number of holes would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Technical loopholes", which he held on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops modified asphalts with polymers in order to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Mrera Nájera said that this type of modified asphalt in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, should be used to improve the behaviour of the road floor and thus avoid the emergence of strike holes.
He explained that the asphalt - the most difficult part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound of which one part has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malts. Together, they give the road cloth its characteristic zehelastic behaviour.
Zehelastic behaviour of the asphalt means that at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very smooth and at 50°C fast, while it becomes fragile at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of asphalt on the streets is not uniform, but changes on one day depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer explained.
The researcher of the FQ noted that the streets of Mexico City had mostly a flexible road coating consisting of six materials layers, of which the last three were asphalt.
Between the top layers lies a sliding layer of asphalt, consisting of small stones baked in asphalt and then fortified.
Each single stone of this wear layer was bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on and produce forces, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer," he explained, "is a last layer designed, the so-called wear layer consisting of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it has to friction.
The most of the strengths of this road covering is received and distributed, the bearing layer also needs an adequate thickness and the material it consists of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to be taken into account, especially water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the site gets wet, water enters the layer and only becomes difficult to return. This causes a revitalization of all layers of the road surface and consequently the appearance of blowholes.
"When a blowhole arises," he said, "it will first be carried off the ceiling layer, while the wear layer will only be affected after that. But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that should be maintained with the first signs through appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (Mexican National Research System) said that the vehicle load was another important cause for hit holes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road coating should always be proportionate to the vehicle load and it should be ensured that this regulation is complied with in order to avoid frequent hit holes.
